snippet.textDisplay:
Guys very moving video.

When I lost my wife of 20 years, in my grief, I came across the beautiful words of the poet Wallace Stevens:

“When fear meets death it becomes pity.
When love meets death it becomes compassion.”

Matt, your friendship, love and words for Xavier were so compassionate. Young man, you have the poet about you.

Keep on keep on

Best, Steve

snippet.textDisplay: This story really hits home. My brother’s kidneys weren’t functioning and he had to go to dialysis. I remember him telling my mom “I never want to get into dialysis” as a young kid, he has had a problem with his kidneys ever since he was a kid and he’s been in and out of hospitals. He’s wanted to give up and he kept telling us he felt he wouldn’t live up to his 20s or have kids. He made it to his 20s and has 2 beautiful kids now all thanks to a kidney donor. Thank you to my mom for donating hers and his donor.

snippet.textDisplay: This video has killed me, motivated me, empowered me so on and so fourth. I truly wish I could’ve met Xavier due to the strength he had. I was moved by his power because it’s the same power every warrior has. When I was 15 I was hit by a car. They told my mother that I would either pass, stay in a vegetative state or wake up mentally in in a wheelchair mentally ill for the rest of my life and I as well surpassed all odds. I don’t mean to share my story after what this story played out to be but my point is strong people can and will surpass all odds. I miss  Xavier and I don’t even know him but stating that means that he is still with us and he more than certainly has lived a legacy in this life. Xavier, I 110% am sure is in heaven looking down smiling at all of your successes and can’t wait to see you guys with the angels.

Hey Yes Theory! To be honest i am one of those viewers who watches videos but never interacts in the comments, I'm a silent viewer. At the time of me posting this comment, there are over 8000 comments so the chances of this being seen are probably slim but this video has pulled me out from my silent watching. I truly appreciate you guys not stepping away from talking about a subject that effects every single person on earth but no one seems to want to talk about it. Death. There I said the big, scary word and it turns out that it wasn't that scary to say after all.


My brother was 26 years old when he tragically died while camping with his girlfriend and their 18 month old son...he was struck by lightning. There is nothing that can prepare you for this kind of news and there is not much that can help you grieve through the loss of someone close to you. However with that being said the one that I have found throughout the years is that we all seek human connection especially when faced with death. Death makes us reflect on what is truly important in life and it makes us cherish those still with us even more. Why do you think people have funerals?? The funeral is more for us living people than it is for the one who passed away because we seek out comfort in those who are also hurting and we don't want to be alone in our hurting. Anyways this video was amazing!

snippet.textDisplay: Watched the video now instead of Sunday right away because I was too scared to face something so deep and touching. I have to say, this has to be one of, if not the best, video on Youtube. This video is a life-lesson! It made me think of my late grandmother who died of lung cancer in 2004. Life is such a blessing and so wonderful but we take everything for granted and are very casual. We all have to be like Luke, spreading positivity, show emotions without holding back and being there for our loved ones. And we have to be like Xavier and face hardships with a fight, a will to never give up. He is the perfect example of defying the odds. I'm genuinely so happy to have found this community, all those like-minded people & Yes Theory. It made me a better person and you guys are something that pushes humanity into the right direction and this gives me hope. Much love everybody. Much love. <3
